lead_paragraph: Forty years after it first appeared on Broadway, ''Hair,'' the exuberant musical that is possibly the most enduring cultural artifact of hippiedom, was revived in Central Park in New York City on Thursday. What few recall, however, is that ''Hair'' had more than its share of misfortune; six members of the original company died prematurely, AIDS and drugs being the prime culprits. ''It's as though everything in 'Hair' turned into a nightmare,'' the executive producer of the original Broadway production, Bertrand Castelli, said in a recent documentary film about the show, ''Hair: Let the Sun Shine In.'' ''Everything that was joyful and harmless became dangerous and ugly.''

Cameron DeVore, a First Amendment lawyer who was an early expert in the field, representing news companies in many significant disputes over the freedom of the press, died on Sunday at his home on Lopez Island, near Seattle. United States, which defined the limits of government-news media regulation.

lead_paragraph: An obituary on July 25 about Paul Bentley, the Dallas police detective who helped arrest Lee Harvey Oswald after the assassination of President John F. Kennedy, included incorrectly, without qualifying its source, a remark Mr. Bentley remembered hearing after the arrest. Many years later, Mr. Bentley told oral history interviewers that on the road to police headquarters with Oswald, after hearing police dispatchers say the man in custody was a prime suspect in the assassination of Kennedy, he asked Oswald, ''Did you shoot President Kennedy?'' and that Oswald replied, ''You find out for yourself.'' Mr. Bentley's recollection is unsupported by other existing historical records. The obituary also described Mr. Bentley's role in the arrest imprecisely. Mr. Bentley adjusted the handcuffs after Oswald complained they were too tight; he did not snap the handcuffs on. (Another officer had placed his handcuffs on Oswald moments earlier.)

lead_paragraph: AUBERT-GOERING-Corinne, died a serene, peaceful death at the youthful, beautiful age of 51 years old on Tuesday, October 22, 2008, leaving her husband Kevin and daughter Camille, 14 (writer of this obituary). Born in Boulogne, France to parents Colette and Claude Aubert, Corinne grew up moving around France with her two sisters Laurence and Nathalie. She began studying in Hippocagne but her powerful, charismatic character drove her towards bigger and better things. She proceeded to complete her bachelor's degrees in Art History and Literature. She met my father, Kevin Goering, in Bordeaux where he was studying the French language. Together, they packed up and ventured to America to begin a new life in the Promised Land. My mother proceeded to begin her work at Yves Saint Laurent, Rive Gauche. She ended her 20 year career in the fashion industry when I, demanding little toddler that I was, kept her home for myself. Mom was a beautiful, intelligent and energetic woman. She particularly enjoyed dragging me on long walks in the wilderness of the Catskills as well as teaching and helping others. This year, she was working with the old and dying to put a stop to suffering and pain. She was full of generosity and compassion for people in general because of how much she had been through herself; she was a tough cookie. This is the one thing she couldn't get through. I write this today with a hint of humor and uplifting thoughts because I do not wish for her to be remembered because she died, but because of the beautiful life that she led. She left a deep impact on all of those people that she encountered in her lifetime and I can only aspire to be like her; my mother, ma maman.
